  pages={1-1},
  abstract={Satellite-derived chlorophyll-a (Chl-a) data are crucial for monitoring and understanding aquatic ecosystems. However, existing satellite Chl-a products are typically sensor-specific, requiring separate model development and calibration for each sensor, which introduces inconsistencies and complicates multi-sensor data merging. This proof-of-concept study proposes a novel transformer-based framework to ingest spectral data from different sensors with one unified model. A key innovation of this model is to learn latent representations of the spectral response functions (SRF) and top-of-atmosphere (TOA) reflectance, as opposed to the typical approach to treat each band with a nominal central wavelength. Additionally, this study presents a simple yet effective augmentation method for satellite match-up datasets containing TOA reflectance paired with field-measured Chl-a. By training on a combined augmented MODIS, MERIS, VIIRS, and OLCI matchup datasets, the transformer-based sensor-agnostic model achieves encouraging results. Specifically, the model-derived Chl-a aligns well with field observations, captures realistic oceanographic features, and maintains robust inter-sensor consistency. Although its performance is below that of four baseline models trained separately for each individual sensor, the transformer architecture has unmatched generalization capability due to inherent parameter-sharing mechanisms—such as shared feature embeddings across bands and uniform attention structures across samples. Beyond Chl-a a retrieval, this transformer-based architecture holds considerable promise as a foundation model for ocean color remote sensing, capable of flexible adaptation across diverse satellite platforms.},
  keywords={Satellite broadcasting;Data models;Satellites;Transformers;Signal to noise ratio;Optical sensors;Training;MODIS;Image color analysis;Sea measurements},
  doi={10.1109/TGRS.2025.3599368},
  ISSN={1558-0644},
